<a name="part-2"></a>
# PART 2 — SUBJECT & CURRICULUM PLANNING

## A. How Many Subjects Should Exist

For Grades 4 and 5: **2 subjects per grade = 4 subject instances total**

| Grade | Subject 1 | Subject 2 |
|-------|-----------|-----------|
| 4 | Mathematics | Science |
| 5 | Mathematics | Science |

> **Why only 2?**  
> For a young student audience, fewer subjects with deeper content beats more subjects with shallow content. Starting with 2 subjects makes the app achievable to build fully, and structured enough to feel complete. Additional subjects (English, Social Studies) can be added as v2 expansions.

---

## B. How Many Grades Should Exist

**2 grades: Grade 4 and Grade 5.**

This serves the 9–11 age group, which is a coherent learning stage. Grade 4 is the entry point; Grade 5 is slightly more advanced. The student picks their grade on login — they only ever see their own grade's content. This prevents confusion and keeps content age-appropriate.

---

## C. How Many Lessons Each Subject Should Have

**10 lessons per subject per grade.**

This is the sweet spot.

| Factor | Why 10 Works |
|--------|-------------|
| **Completion** | 10 lessons can be completed in 2–3 weeks of regular use |
| **Structure** | Easy (3) → Medium (4) → Hard (3) provides a clear arc |
| **Scope** | Deep enough to cover a meaningful curriculum unit |
| **Motivation** | A 10-step progress bar feels achievable, not overwhelming |
| **Development** | 40 total lessons (4 subjects × 10) is a full, shippable v1 product |

---

## D. Lesson Arrangement Logic: Easy → Medium → Hard

```
Lessons 1–3   → EASY    (foundational concepts, direct recall)
Lessons 4–7   → MEDIUM  (applying concepts, multi-step thinking)
Lessons 8–10  → HARD    (complex problems, synthesis, real-world application)
```

This follows **Bloom's Taxonomy** — you always build from remembering → understanding → applying.

---

